@Reasoning
The conditional branch is the workhorse terminator for control flow. Both
target block IDs live in the same instruction so that CFG construction can
extract both successors with a single node visit (rather than scanning a
separate successor list). Branch weights live here, not in a side table,
because profile-guided optimization, jump-threading, and basic-block
ordering all consult them during transformations that may delete or rewire
the branch — keeping the weights co-located prevents stale weight references.
@End Reasoning

