    Let throw_size be 24
    Let throw be proc allocate from Layout with throw_size

    If throw is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base be proc create_mir_node from MIR with MIR.MIR_THROW
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with throw, 0, base
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with throw, 8, exception_value_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with throw, 16, exception_type

    If base is not equal to 0:
        proc set_mir_node_operand from MIR with base, 1, exception_value_id
        proc set_mir_node_type from MIR with base, exception_type
    End If

    Return throw
End Process

@Reasoning
Debug values bridge SSA back to source semantics so debuggers and crash
dumps can show "this value is variable foo declared at file:line:col".
They are pseudo-instructions: they don't compute anything, they only
annotate. Keeping them in the instruction stream (rather than a parallel
side table) means they ride along through every optimization without
needing separate update logic — if an optimization moves the underlying
value, the debug node moves with it because it sits in the same block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Creates a debug value annotation that associates an SSA value with a source
variable name and location. Essential for debugger variable inspection.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_mir_debug_value" that takes value_id as Integer, variable_name as Integer, source_file as Integer, source_line as Integer, source_column as Integer, scope_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let debug_size be 56
    Let debug be proc allocate from Layout with debug_size

    If debug is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base be proc create_mir_node from MIR with MIR.MIR_DEBUG_VALUE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with debug, 0, base
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with debug, 8, value_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with debug, 16, variable_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with debug, 24, source_file
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with debug, 32, source_line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with debug, 40, source_column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with debug, 48, scope_id

    If base is not equal to 0:
        proc set_mir_node_operand from MIR with base, 1, value_id
    End If

    Return debug
End Process

@Reasoning
Debug locations carry the source position attached to one MIR instruction.
They are the input to stack-trace generation and to source-line stepping
in a debugger. The inlined_at field is critical for correct backtraces in
inlined code: it stores the call site that triggered the inlining, so
the debugger can show both the inlined source location and the call site
from which it was inlined (giving a proper "inlined from foo:42" frame).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Creates a debug location marker that annotates an instruction with its
source location. Enables accurate stack traces and source-level debugging.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_mir_debug_location" that takes source_file as Integer, source_line as Integer, source_column as Integer, scope_id as Integer, inlined_at as Integer returns Integer:
    Let loc_size be 48
    Let loc be proc allocate from Layout with loc_size

    If loc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base be proc create_mir_node from MIR with MIR.MIR_DEBUG_LOCATION
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loc, 0, base
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loc, 8, source_file
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loc, 16, source_line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loc, 24, source_column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loc, 32, scope_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loc, 40, inlined_at

    Return loc
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Specialized Node Access Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the MIR opcode of an instruction. Called from MIR optimization passes
(inlining cost analysis, dead code elimination, common subexpression elimination)
that need to dispatch on opcode without depending on the specialized node accessors
in mir.runa. Centralizing opcode access here lets MIRNodes serve as the canonical
access boundary for all MIR instruction introspection used by middle-end passes.

The opcode is stored at byte offset 0 of every MIRNode (verified by the MIRNode
type definition in mir.runa: opcode is the first field, occupying bytes 0-7).
Specialized nodes (MIRPhiNode, MIRBinaryOp, etc.) wrap a base MIRNode pointer
at offset 0 — but callers that hold a specialized-node pointer should use
MIR.get_mir_node_opcode on the base pointer they extracted, not this proc.
This proc expects a MIRNode pointer (the kind stored in basic-block instruction
lists by mir.add_instruction_to_block).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Performs a single 8-byte load at offset 0 of the instruction pointer. Defends
against null inputs by returning 0 (matching the sentinel used by every other
accessor in this file and by MIR.get_mir_node_opcode in mir.runa). No allocation,
no dispatch, no auxiliary lookups — purely a typed memory read through the
Layout primitive so allocator-aware semantics (Tier 3 OWNED HEAP) are honored.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot path: called once per instruction in inlining cost analysis (inlining.runa
line 405) and once per instruction during inlining transform iteration (line 637).
For a function with N instructions visited by the inliner, this runs O(N) times.
Single int64 load is a candidate for inlining by the backend; the null check
adds one compare-and-branch but is predicted not-taken in production input.
No heap traffic, no syscalls, no string formatting — strictly arithmetic.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only operation on caller-provided pointer. Validates non-null before
dereferencing. Does not modify the instruction, does not expose internal
state beyond the opcode value, does not propagate caller pointers. The
opcode value returned is a numeric constant in the documented MIR opcode
range (20000-20999) — leaking it carries no security implication beyond
revealing the structural shape of the MIR, which is intentional public API.
No untrusted-input path: callers in the optimization pipeline operate on
MIR produced by the compiler itself, not on user-controlled byte streams.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_opcode" that takes inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
The phi pair-count field (offset 24) is the cheap source of truth for
how many predecessor edges this phi merges. CFG dominance verification
and copy-propagation read this constantly while scanning a function's
phi nodes, so making it a single int64 load (rather than computing
list-length / 2) keeps it O(1) and branch-free.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_phi_incoming_count" that takes phi as Integer returns Integer:
    If phi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi, 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Decodes the value half of the Nth phi incoming pair. Pairs are stored as
two consecutive list elements (block at 2N, value at 2N+1) so the index
math compresses one multiply and one add. The SSA renamer and copy
propagation both need value lookup keyed by pair index.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_phi_incoming_value" that takes phi as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If phi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let incoming_pairs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi, 16
    Let pair_index be index multiplied by 2 plus 1
    Return proc get from List with incoming_pairs, pair_index
End Process

@Reasoning
Block side of the phi pair (offset 2N in the list). CFG-aware passes
(loop simplification, edge splitting) iterate pairs by predecessor, so
having direct block lookup avoids constructing a temporary tuple just
to read one half.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_phi_incoming_block" that takes phi as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If phi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let incoming_pairs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi, 16
    Let pair_index be index multiplied by 2
    Return proc get from List with incoming_pairs, pair_index
End Process

@Reasoning
Left operand of a binary op (offset 16 in MIRBinaryOp). Constant folding,
