@Reasoning
Element type (offset 48) — the type of one lane of the vector. Combined
with width, this fully describes the vector layout. The backend picks
the lane size from the type's bit width when computing the total
vector size.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_vector_element_type" that takes vector as Integer returns Integer:
    If vector is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with vector, 48
End Process

@Reasoning
Mask/shuffle data (offset 56). Non-zero only for shuffle, blend, and
gather/scatter opcodes that select per-lane behavior. Encoded as a
packed byte sequence (one byte per lane index or per lane predicate)
so it fits in a single int64 for narrow vectors and as a pointer to
external storage for wider ones.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_vector_mask_data" that takes vector as Integer returns Integer:
    If vector is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with vector, 56
End Process

Note: Exception Handling Accessors

@Reasoning
Invoke callee (offset 16) — same encoding as call.callee. Inlining is
allowed to remove the exception edges if it proves the inlinee cannot
throw, in which case it would replace this node with a plain call.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_invoke_callee" that takes invoke as Integer returns Integer:
    If invoke is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Invoke arguments list (offset 24). Mirrors call.arguments but lives on
the invoke node so the two opcodes share layout up through offset 40.
Argument-promotion runs over both equally.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_invoke_arguments" that takes invoke as Integer returns Integer:
    If invoke is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Invoke argument count (offset 32). Cached length, kept consistent with
the list by the constructor and any argument-modifying pass.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_invoke_argument_count" that takes invoke as Integer returns Integer:
    If invoke is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Normal-return successor (offset 48) — taken when the invoked callee
returns without throwing. The CFG must see this edge to keep dominance
correct, and most optimization passes treat it as the "fall-through"
side of the invoke.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_invoke_normal_block" that takes invoke as Integer returns Integer:
    If invoke is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 48
End Process

@Reasoning
Exception successor (offset 56) — taken when the invoked callee
unwinds. Marks the entry to a landing-pad block. Cleanup-elimination
may rewire this edge, but it cannot remove it as long as the callee
may throw.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_invoke_exception_block" that takes invoke as Integer returns Integer:
    If invoke is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 56
End Process

@Reasoning
Exception-type field on a landing pad (offset 16) — the runtime type
descriptor used to match incoming throws against this pad. The runtime
uses RTTI on the thrown value to find a matching catch.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_landingpad_exception_type" that takes landingpad as Integer returns Integer:
    If landingpad is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with landingpad, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Catch clauses list (offset 24). Each clause is a (type_id, block_id)
pair stored as two consecutive list elements, in source order. The
runtime tests them in order, so optimizations that reorder clauses
must preserve the "first match wins" semantics.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_landingpad_catch_clauses" that takes landingpad as Integer returns Integer:
    If landingpad is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with landingpad, 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Cached catch-clause count (offset 32). Lockstep with the clauses list.
Cleanup-elimination and clause-merging both consult this count when
deciding whether the landing pad has been reduced to a single trivial
clause that can be folded out.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_landingpad_clause_count" that takes landingpad as Integer returns Integer:
    If landingpad is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with landingpad, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Cleanup successor (offset 40) — taken when no catch clause matches but
the pad still has cleanup actions (RAII-like destructors, finally
blocks). The runtime jumps here after executing cleanup, then re-raises
the exception to continue unwinding.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_landingpad_cleanup_block" that takes landingpad as Integer returns Integer:
    If landingpad is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with landingpad, 40
End Process

@Reasoning
Thrown SSA value (offset 8). The exception object that will be raised.
Unwinding inspects this value's runtime type to find a matching landing
pad. Exception-flow analysis can fold a throw whose value flows directly
from a catch with no transformation.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_throw_exception_value" that takes throw as Integer returns Integer:
    If throw is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with throw, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Static type tag on a throw (offset 16). Lets static analysis match
throws to catches without inspecting runtime RTTI — useful for proving
that a throw cannot escape a given function (so the callee's invoke
edges can be trimmed).
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_throw_exception_type" that takes throw as Integer returns Integer:
    If throw is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with throw, 16
End Process

Note: Debug Info Accessors

@Reasoning
SSA value id (offset 8) that a debug-value annotation is shadowing. Reads
the SSA value the debug node is tracking on behalf of a source variable.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_debug_value_id" that takes debug as Integer returns Integer:
    If debug is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Original source variable name (offset 16). String-table pointer kept on
the debug node so dumps and debuggers can map the SSA name back to source.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_debug_variable_name" that takes debug as Integer returns Integer:
    If debug is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Source file (offset 24) — string pointer to the file path the variable
declaration came from. Used by debuggers to navigate to the declaration.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_debug_source_file" that takes debug as Integer returns Integer:
    If debug is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Source line (offset 32) — 1-based line number where the variable was
declared. Combined with file gives the precise source position.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_debug_source_line" that takes debug as Integer returns Integer:
    If debug is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Source column (offset 40) — 1-based column. DWARF emitters use line+col
to generate the .debug_line table that maps PC ranges to source positions.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_debug_source_column" that takes debug as Integer returns Integer:
    If debug is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 40
End Process

@Reasoning
Debug scope id (offset 48) — identifies the lexical block, function, or
namespace the variable belongs to. Scope information enables correct
variable-shadowing behavior in debuggers.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_debug_scope_id" that takes debug as Integer returns Integer:
    If debug is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 48
End Process

@Reasoning
Location source file (offset 8 in MIRDebugLocation). Distinct from
MIRDebugValue: location nodes attach to instructions, not values, and
drive stack-trace line numbers rather than variable inspection.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_location_source_file" that takes loc as Integer returns Integer:
    If loc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loc, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Location source line (offset 16). Drives the .debug_line PC→line mapping
that the runtime consults for backtrace formatting.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_location_source_line" that takes loc as Integer returns Integer:
    If loc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loc, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Location source column (offset 24). Column-aware backtraces let crash
dumps point at the exact expression that raised an error, not just the
containing line.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_location_source_column" that takes loc as Integer returns Integer:
    If loc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loc, 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Location scope id (offset 32). Different from the debug-value scope because
locations track lexical block identity for instruction-level granularity
(useful when single-stepping through inlined code).
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_location_scope_id" that takes loc as Integer returns Integer:
    If loc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loc, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Inlined-at marker (offset 40). When non-zero, indicates this instruction
came from an inlined function; the value is the call-site location id of
the original call. Debuggers use this to reconstruct virtual frames so
inlined code appears as a proper inline stack frame in backtraces.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_location_inlined_at" that takes loc as Integer returns Integer:
    If loc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loc, 40
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Specialized Debug Printing Functions
Note: Format instructions in human-readable SSA form for optimizer debugging
Note: ============================================================================

@Implementation
Formats a phi node as: %result = phi type [%val1, block1], [%val2, block2], ...
Example: %3 = phi i32 [%1, block_0], [%2, block_1]
@End Implementation

@Reasoning
Phi node debug-print produces "%N = phi [%val, block_K], ..." in LLVM-ish
style so MIR dumps are familiar to compiler engineers and so the verifier's
error messages can quote the exact offending node. The constructed string
is heap-owned so callers must deallocate it; per-pair concatenation is
deliberate to keep the printer's allocator footprint linear in pair count
rather than super-linear.
@End Reasoning

Process called "phi_node_to_string" that takes phi as Integer returns Integer:
    If phi is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null phi>"
    End If

    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi, 8
    Let incoming_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi, 24

    Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id
    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "%"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = phi"
    proc deallocate from Layout with result_str

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than incoming_count:
        Let block_id be proc get_phi_incoming_block with phi, i
        Let value_id be proc get_phi_incoming_value with phi, i

        Let block_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with block_id
        Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with value_id

        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " [%"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", block_"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, block_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "]"

        proc deallocate from Layout with block_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with value_str

        If i is less than incoming_count minus 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ","
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Binop debug-print mirrors LLVM IR conventions so dumps can be diffed
across compilers when porting tests. Pulling the opcode through the base
MIRNode (rather than caching it on the binop) keeps a single source of
truth for opcode and avoids two locations to update if MIR opcode numbering
ever shifts.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a binary operation as: %result = opcode type %left, %right
Example: %5 = add i32 %3, %4
@End Implementation

Process called "binary_op_to_string" that takes binop as Integer returns Integer:
    If binop is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null binop>"
    End If

    Let base be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with binop, 0
    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with binop, 8
    Let left_op be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with binop, 16
    Let right_op be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with binop, 24

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with base
    Let opcode_str be proc opcode_to_string from MIR with opcode
    Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id
    Let left_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with left_op
    Let right_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with right_op

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "%"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, opcode_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, left_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, right_str

    proc deallocate from Layout with opcode_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with result_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with left_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with right_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Load debug-print uses LLVM "load ptr %addr" shorthand. The offset is
intentionally elided from the default dump when it would be 0 — explicit
zero offsets clutter the dump for the common direct-load case. Verifier
errors that need the offset use a dedicated, more verbose dump path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a load instruction as: %result = load type, ptr %address
Example: %10 = load i32, ptr %9
@End Implementation

Process called "load_to_string" that takes load as Integer returns Integer:
    If load is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null load>"
    End If

    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with load, 8
    Let address_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with load, 16

    Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id
    Let address_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with address_value_id

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "%"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = load ptr %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, address_str

    proc deallocate from Layout with result_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with address_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Store debug-print follows "store value, ptr addr" so the value-then-ptr
order reads naturally in dumps and matches the LLVM convention. There is
no result_value_id to print because stores produce no SSA value, which
makes the dump shorter than for loads — a visual cue to the reader that
this is a side-effecting node, not a value-producing one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a store instruction as: store type %value, ptr %address
Example: store i32 %5, ptr %6
@End Implementation

Process called "store_to_string" that takes store as Integer returns Integer:
    If store is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null store>"
    End If

    Let address_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with store, 8
    Let value_to_store be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with store, 16

    Let address_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with address_value_id
    Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with value_to_store

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "store %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", ptr %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, address_str

    proc deallocate from Layout with address_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with value_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Call debug-print elides the "%N =" prefix when result_value_id is 0 (void
call) so void calls do not waste characters on a phantom result. Arguments
are pulled from the List and printed comma-separated; the constructed
string keeps the per-argument allocation discipline of the rest of the
printer (each integer-to-string allocation is deallocated immediately
after being concatenated).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a call instruction as: %result = call return_type @function(%arg1, %arg2, ...)
Example: %7 = call i32 @factorial(%6)
@End Implementation

Process called "call_to_string" that takes call as Integer returns Integer:
    If call is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null call>"
    End If

    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call, 8
    Let callee be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call, 16
    Let arguments be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call, 24
    Let argument_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call, 32

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with ""

    If result_value_id is not equal to 0:
        Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "%"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
        proc deallocate from Layout with result_str
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "call @"

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than argument_count:
        Let arg_value_id be proc get from List with arguments, i
        Let arg_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with arg_value_id

        If i is equal to 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "(%"
        Otherwise:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", %"
        End If

        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, arg_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with arg_str

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"

    Return result
End Process

@Implementation
Formats a branch instruction as: br i1 %cond, label %true, label %false
Example: br i1 %2, label %block_1, label %block_2
@End Implementation

@Reasoning
Branch debug-print uses "br i1 %cond, label %true, label %false" to mirror
LLVM IR. The verbose form (with both targets) is preferred over a compact
"branch %cond -> %true | %false" because dumps are read most often during
backend debugging, where matching LLVM convention reduces cognitive load.
@End Reasoning

Process called "branch_to_string" that takes branch as Integer returns Integer:
    If branch is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null branch>"
    End If

    Let condition_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with branch, 8
    Let true_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with branch, 16
    Let false_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with branch, 24

    Let cond_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with condition_value_id
    Let true_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with true_block_id
    Let false_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with false_block_id

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "br i1 %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, cond_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", label %block_"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, true_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", label %block_"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, false_str

    proc deallocate from Layout with cond_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with true_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with false_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Jump debug-print uses "jmp label %target" — short by design because the
unconditional jump is the simplest terminator and visual brevity reinforces
that. Note the deliberate use of "jmp" rather than "br" to make
unconditional vs conditional control flow visually distinct in dumps.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a jump instruction as: jmp label %target
Example: jmp label %block_3
@End Implementation

Process called "jump_to_string" that takes jump as Integer returns Integer:
    If jump is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null jump>"
    End If

    Let target_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with jump, 8
    Let target_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with target_block_id

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "jmp label %block_"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, target_str

    proc deallocate from Layout with target_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Return debug-print switches between "ret void" (no value) and "ret %N"
based on whether return_value_id is zero. The two forms share no
character with each other beyond "ret", so we build them as separate
literals rather than concatenating an optional value suffix — this keeps
the void branch allocation-free and matches the LLVM dump convention.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a return instruction as: ret type %value or ret void
Example: ret i32 %5 or ret void
@End Implementation

Process called "return_to_string" that takes ret as Integer returns Integer:
    If ret is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null return>"
    End If

    Let return_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ret, 8

    If return_value_id is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "ret void"
    End If

    Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with return_value_id
    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "ret %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with value_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Alloca debug-print shows result-id and alignment. The element type is
intentionally elided from the default dump form (the alloca's result
type "%N = alloca, align K" already conveys what is being allocated
through downstream uses); when fuller info is needed, the verifier
uses a dedicated dump path that includes element type and count.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats an alloca instruction as: %result = alloca type, align N
Example: %8 = alloca i32, align 4
@End Implementation

Process called "alloca_to_string" that takes alloca as Integer returns Integer:
    If alloca is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null alloca>"
    End If

    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with alloca, 8
    Let alignment be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with alloca, 32

    Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id
    Let align_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with alignment

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "%"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = alloca, align "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, align_str

    proc deallocate from Layout with result_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with align_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Const debug-print branches on is_string: numeric constants print their
literal value, string constants print the quoted source text. The split
keeps the dump readable for both cases without forcing a single uniform
encoding ("const ptr %0x..." for strings would lose the literal text).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a constant instruction as: %result = const value
Example: %1 = const 42
@End Implementation

Process called "const_to_string" that takes const as Integer returns Integer:
    If const is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null const>"
    End If

    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with const, 8
    Let constant_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with const, 16
    Let is_string be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with const, 32

    Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "%"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = const "

    proc deallocate from Layout with result_str

    If is_string is equal to 1:
        Let string_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with const, 40
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\""
        If string_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, string_ptr
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\""
    Otherwise:
        Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with constant_value
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with value_str
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Switch debug-print iterates every case in order, then appends the default
clause. The "value => block" arrow notation is chosen instead of the LLVM
bracket form because it reads more naturally for the long case lists that
appear in match/dispatch-heavy Runa code. Per-case allocations are freed
immediately after concatenation to keep peak memory bounded.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a switch instruction as: switch %value [ case1 => block1, case2 => block2, default => block_default ]
Example: switch %5 [ 0 => block_1, 1 => block_2, default => block_3 ]
@End Implementation

Process called "switch_to_string" that takes switch as Integer returns Integer:
    If switch is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null switch>"
    End If

    Let value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch, 8
    Let case_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch, 24
    Let default_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch, 32

    Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with value_id
    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "switch %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " ["
    proc deallocate from Layout with value_str

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than case_count:
        Let case_value be proc get_switch_case_value with switch, i
        Let block_id be proc get_switch_case_block with switch, i

        Let case_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with case_value
        Let block_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with block_id

        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, case_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " => block_"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, block_str

        proc deallocate from Layout with case_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with block_str

        If i is less than case_count minus 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ","
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let default_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with default_block_id
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", default => block_"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, default_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " ]"
    proc deallocate from Layout with default_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Atomic-op debug-print spells out the memory-ordering tag (relaxed,
acquire, release, acq_rel, seq_cst) for readability — the numeric tag
would force the reader to remember the encoding. The operand is optional
(zero for atomic loads) so the printer guards each component with a
non-zero check, keeping dumps free of spurious "%0" placeholders.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats an atomic operation as: %result = atomic_op memory_order ptr %addr, %operand
Example: %10 = atomic_add seq_cst ptr %9, %8
@End Implementation

Process called "atomic_op_to_string" that takes atomic as Integer returns Integer:
    If atomic is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null atomic>"
    End If

    Let base be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with atomic, 0
    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with atomic, 8
    Let address_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with atomic, 16
    Let operand_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with atomic, 24
    Let memory_order be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with atomic, 40

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with base
    Let opcode_str be proc opcode_to_string from MIR with opcode

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with ""

    If result_value_id is not equal to 0:
        Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "%"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
        proc deallocate from Layout with result_str
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, opcode_str

    Note: Memory order names
    If memory_order is equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " relaxed"
    End If
    If memory_order is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " acquire"
    End If
    If memory_order is equal to 2:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " release"
    End If
    If memory_order is equal to 3:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " acq_rel"
    End If
    If memory_order is equal to 4:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " seq_cst"
    End If

    Let addr_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with address_value_id
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " ptr %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, addr_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with addr_str

    If operand_value_id is not equal to 0:
        Let op_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with operand_value_id
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", %"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, op_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with op_str
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with opcode_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Vector-op debug-print uses LLVM "<width x type>" shorthand because that
form makes lane count visible at a glance — critical when diffing
vectorization passes that may change width across versions. Operand3 is
elided from the default dump (only FMA and select use it); a verifier-
mode dump path includes operand3 when present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a vector operation as: %result = vector_op <width x type> %op1, %op2
Example: %7 = vector_add <4 x float> %5, %6
@End Implementation

Process called "vector_op_to_string" that takes vector as Integer returns Integer:
    If vector is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null vector>"
    End If

    Let base be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with vector, 0
    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with vector, 8
    Let operand1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with vector, 16
    Let operand2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with vector, 24
    Let vector_width be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with vector, 40

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with base
    Let opcode_str be proc opcode_to_string from MIR with opcode

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with ""

    If result_value_id is not equal to 0:
        Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "%"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
        proc deallocate from Layout with result_str
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, opcode_str

    Let width_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with vector_width
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " <"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, width_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " x type>"
    proc deallocate from Layout with width_str

    If operand1 is not equal to 0:
        Let op1_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with operand1
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " %"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, op1_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with op1_str
    End If

    If operand2 is not equal to 0:
        Let op2_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with operand2
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", %"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, op2_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with op2_str
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with opcode_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Invoke debug-print extends the call-dump form with two label suffixes
("normal:" and "exception:") so both successor edges are visible in
one line. This makes invokes immediately distinguishable from calls in
dumps — important because optimization decisions hinge on the distinction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats an invoke instruction as: %result = invoke @function(%args) normal: block1, exception: block2
Example: %5 = invoke @may_throw(%3, %4) normal: block_2, exception: block_3
@End Implementation


Process called "invoke_to_string" that takes invoke as Integer returns Integer:
    If invoke is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null invoke>"
    End If

    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 8
    Let argument_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 32
    Let normal_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 48
    Let exception_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 56
    Let arguments be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke, 24

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with ""

    If result_value_id is not equal to 0:
        Let result_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with result_value_id
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "%"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, result_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
        proc deallocate from Layout with result_str
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "invoke @function("

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than argument_count:
        Let arg_value_id be proc get from List with arguments, i
        Let arg_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with arg_value_id

        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
        End If

        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "%"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, arg_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with arg_str

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ") normal: block_"

    Let normal_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with normal_block_id
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, normal_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", exception: block_"
    proc deallocate from Layout with normal_str

    Let exception_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with exception_block_id
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, exception_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with exception_str

    Return result
End Process


@Reasoning
Throw debug-print is intentionally minimal — "throw %N" — because the
thrown value's type and runtime metadata are inspected at the catch
site, not at the throw. The verbose form including exception_type is
reserved for verifier output where exception-type tracking matters.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a throw instruction as: throw type %exception
Example: throw Exception %10
@End Implementation


Process called "throw_to_string" that takes throw as Integer returns Integer:
    If throw is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null throw>"
    End If

    Let exception_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with throw, 8

    Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with exception_value_id
    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "throw %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with value_str

    Return result
End Process


@Reasoning
Debug-value debug-print includes the source variable name in quotes plus
the source location triple. This matches how DWARF reads in dumpers, so
debugger-format diffs against MIR dumps remain meaningful. Unknown
file paths are replaced with "<unknown>" to keep the format positionally
stable for downstream regex-based tooling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Formats a debug value annotation as: debug_value %value "variable_name" at file:line:column
Example: debug_value %5 "counter" at main.runa:42:10
@End Implementation


Process called "debug_value_to_string" that takes debug as Integer returns Integer:
    If debug is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null debug>"
    End If

    Let value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 8
    Let variable_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 16
    Let source_file be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 24
    Let source_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 32
    Let source_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with debug, 40

    Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with value_id
    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "debug_value %"
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with value_str

    If variable_name is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " \""
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, variable_name
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\""
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " at "

    If source_file is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, source_file
    Otherwise:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "<unknown>"
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ":"
    Let line_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with source_line
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, line_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ":"
    proc deallocate from Layout with line_str

    Let col_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with source_column
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, col_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with col_str

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: BLOCK ID ACCESSORS FOR CFG CONSTRUCTION
Note: These functions return block IDs from terminator instructions
Note: Used by cfg.runa for control flow graph construction
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
CFG construction needs branch successor block IDs as fully-resolved Integer
labels, not as raw MIRBranch fields. This accessor returns the true target
with -1 sentinel on null input so the CFG builder can distinguish a missing
target from block ID 0 (block 0 is the function entry block, a valid value).
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_branch_true_block" that takes branch as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the true target block ID from a MIRBranch instruction.
    Returns -1 if branch pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If branch is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with branch, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Mirror of get_mir_branch_true_block for the false successor. Two distinct
accessors (rather than an indexed accessor) make CFG-construction code
self-documenting: "true_succ = ..., false_succ = ..." reads cleaner than
"succ_0 = ..., succ_1 = ...". Same -1 sentinel discipline for null inputs.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_branch_false_block" that takes branch as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the false target block ID from a MIRBranch instruction.
    Returns -1 if branch pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If branch is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with branch, 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the single successor of an unconditional jump for CFG construction.
The -1 sentinel preserves the convention used by the branch accessors
above so the CFG builder can treat all terminator successors uniformly
(any -1 means "skip this edge").
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_jump_target_block" that takes jump as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the target block ID from a MIRJump instruction.
    Returns -1 if jump pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If jump is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with jump, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
CFG construction needs to iterate every case in a switch to discover all
successor edges. Returning the cached count (offset 24) lets the builder
size its iteration without paying the cost of inspecting the case-list
List for its length. Returns 0 on null input rather than -1 because the
"no cases" interpretation is valid for both null switches and switches
with all cases removed.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_switch_case_count" that takes switch_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the number of case clauses in a MIRSwitch instruction.
    Returns 0 if switch pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If switch_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch_ptr, 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Default-case target accessor used during CFG leader identification: every
basic-block leader must include the default destination, otherwise the
CFG misses an edge and dominance becomes wrong. Returns 0 on null input
because the leader-identification pass treats 0 as "skip" rather than
attempting to read it as a valid target.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_switch_default_target" that takes switch_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the default target (as instruction/value, not block ID) from a MIRSwitch.
    This is used for identifying leaders during CFG construction.
    Returns 0 if switch pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If switch_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Default block ID is at offset 32
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch_ptr, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Per-case target accessor used during CFG leader identification. Reads
the case-list entry at case_idx (an index pair structure stored at offset
8) and returns the block_id. Bounds-checks both negative and out-of-range
indices because CFG construction iterates by index and would otherwise
read past the case list.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_switch_case_target" that takes switch_ptr as Integer, case_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the target value/instruction for a specific case in a MIRSwitch.
    Used for identifying leaders during CFG construction.
    Returns 0 if switch pointer is equal to 0 or case_idx is out of bounds.
    @End Implementation

    If switch_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let case_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch_ptr, 24

    If case_idx is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If case_idx is greater than or equal to case_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get the cases list pointer (offset 16)
    Let cases_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch_ptr, 16

    If cases_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Each case is a pair (case_value, block_id)
    Note: We need the block_id which is the second element of the pair
    Note: Assuming list_get returns pointer to pair, and block_id is at offset 8 in the pair
    Let case_pair be proc list_get from List with cases_list, case_idx

    If case_pair is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Return the block_id from the pair (second field, offset 8)
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with case_pair, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Block-ID accessor (vs the "default_target" variant above) — uses the -1
sentinel because CFG-edge construction needs to distinguish between "no
default" and "default is block 0". Block 0 (function entry) is a legal
default target in some lowering schemes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_switch_default_block" that takes switch_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the default block ID from a MIRSwitch instruction.
    Returns -1 if switch pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If switch_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch_ptr, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Block-ID variant of get_mir_switch_case_target, with the same bounds-check
discipline but the -1 sentinel for CFG-edge consumers. Two accessors
(target vs block) exist because CFG construction works at two layers:
leader identification (uses raw target) and edge enumeration (uses block ID).
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_switch_case_block" that takes switch_ptr as Integer, case_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the target block ID for a specific case in a MIRSwitch.
    Returns -1 if switch pointer is equal to 0 or case_idx is out of bounds.
    @End Implementation

    If switch_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If

    Let case_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch_ptr, 24

    If case_idx is less than 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If

    If case_idx is greater than or equal to case_count:
        Return negative 1
    End If

    Note: Get the cases list pointer (offset 16)
    Let cases_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with switch_ptr, 16

    If cases_list is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If

    Note: Each case is a pair (case_value, block_id)
    Let case_pair be proc list_get from List with cases_list, case_idx

    If case_pair is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If

    Note: Return the block_id from the pair (second field, offset 8)
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with case_pair, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Normal-successor accessor for invoke nodes, raw-target form. CFG leader
identification visits this to mark the normal-return block as a leader.
Returns 0 on null so the leader-identification driver can treat 0 as
"skip" and continue walking the function uniformly.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_invoke_normal_dest" that takes invoke_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the normal destination target (as instruction/value, not block ID) from MIRInvoke.
    Used for identifying leaders during CFG construction.
    Returns 0 if invoke pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If invoke_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Normal block ID is at offset 48
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke_ptr, 48
End Process

@Reasoning
Exception-edge accessor for invoke, raw-target form. The exception
successor block must also be a leader so exception-handling code lives
in its own block. Same 0-sentinel discipline as the normal-dest accessor.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_invoke_unwind_dest" that takes invoke_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the exception/unwind destination target (as instruction/value, not block ID) from MIRInvoke.
    Used for identifying leaders during CFG construction.
    Returns 0 if invoke pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If invoke_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Exception block ID is at offset 56
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke_ptr, 56
End Process

@Reasoning
Block-ID variant of get_mir_invoke_normal_dest. CFG edge construction
consumes block IDs (not raw targets), so this accessor exists alongside
its raw-target sibling. -1 sentinel matches the other block-ID accessors
in this section so the CFG builder's null handling stays uniform.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_invoke_normal_block" that takes invoke_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the normal destination block ID from a MIRInvoke instruction.
    Returns -1 if invoke pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If invoke_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke_ptr, 48
End Process

@Reasoning
Block-ID variant of get_mir_invoke_unwind_dest. Pairs with the normal-
block accessor to give the CFG builder both successor edges of an invoke
in the same -1-sentinel format used by the rest of this section.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_mir_invoke_unwind_block" that takes invoke_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Implementation
    Returns the exception/unwind block ID from a MIRInvoke instruction.
    Returns -1 if invoke pointer is null.
    @End Implementation

    If invoke_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return negative 1
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with invoke_ptr, 56
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: PHI NODE HELPER FUNCTIONS FOR SSA CONSTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================

Process called "is_phi_node" that takes inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Checks if an instruction is a phi node.

    This is used during SSA construction to identify and process phi nodes.
    Phi nodes must be at the beginning of basic blocks before all other instructions.

    We check if the instruction's opcode is MIR_PHI.

    Returns: 1 if phi node, 0 otherwise
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get opcode from MIRNode (offset 0)
    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 0

    Note: Check if opcode is MIR_PHI (20013)
    If opcode is equal to MIR.MIR_PHI:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "get_phi_variable_name" that takes phi_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Gets the variable name for a phi node from its metadata.

    For SSA construction, we need to track which variable each phi node represents.
    This function looks up the original source variable name from the phi node's
    metadata. If no metadata exists, returns a descriptive SSA name "phi_N".

    Returns: Variable name string pointer, or 0 on failure
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If phi_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if actually a phi node
    Let is_phi be proc is_phi_node with phi_ptr
    If is_phi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get base MIRNode pointer (offset 0 in MIRPhiNode)
    Let base_node be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 0

    If base_node is not equal to 0:
        Note: Get metadata from base node (offset 64 in MIRNode)
        Let metadata_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base_node, 64

        If metadata_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Get variable name from metadata
            Let variable_name be proc get_metadata_variable_name with metadata_ptr

            If variable_name is not equal to 0:
                Note: Found variable name in metadata - return it
                Return variable_name
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: No metadata or no variable name - return descriptive SSA name
    Note: PHI nodes represent SSA values, so "phi_N" is appropriate for IR
    Let result_value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 8
    Let name_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 64

    Note: Create string "phi_"
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 0, 112  Note: 'p'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 1, 104  Note: 'h'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 2, 105  Note: 'i'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 3, 95   Note: '_'

    Note: Convert value_id to string
    Let pos be 4
    Let temp_value be result_value_id
    Let digit_count be 0

    Note: Count digits
    Let temp_copy be temp_value
    While temp_copy is greater than 0:
        Set temp_copy to temp_copy divided by 10
        Set digit_count to digit_count plus 1
    End While

    Note: Handle zero case
    If digit_count is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos, 48  Note: '0'
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Note: Extract digits
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than digit_count:
            Let digit be temp_value modulo by 10
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos plus digit_count minus i minus 1, digit plus 48
            Set temp_value to temp_value divided by 10
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set pos to pos plus digit_count
    End If

    Note: Null terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos, 0

    Return name_buffer
End Process

Process called "get_phi_result_type" that takes phi_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Gets the result type (HIRTypeInfo pointer) of a phi node.

    MIRPhi structure (48 bytes):
    - Offset 0: base MIRNode pointer
    - Offset 8: result_value_id
    - Offset 16: incoming_pairs list
    - Offset 24: incoming_count
    - Offset 32: result_type (HIRTypeInfo pointer)
    - Offset 40: parent_block

    Returns: HIRTypeInfo pointer, or 0 on failure
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If phi_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if actually a phi node
    Let is_phi be proc is_phi_node with phi_ptr
    If is_phi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get result_type from MIRPhi (offset 32)
    Let result_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 32
    Return result_type
End Process

Process called "set_phi_result_value_id" that takes phi_ptr as Integer, new_value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Sets the result value ID of a phi node.

    This is used during SSA construction renaming phase to assign fresh SSA names
    to phi node results.

    MIRPhi structure:
    - Offset 8: result_value_id (update this field)

    Also needs to update the base MIRNode's value_id.

    Returns: 1 on success, 0 on failure
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If phi_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if actually a phi node
    Let is_phi be proc is_phi_node with phi_ptr
    If is_phi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set result_value_id in MIRPhi structure (offset 8)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 8, new_value_id

    Note: Also update base MIRNode's value_id (offset 0 = base pointer, then offset 8 in base)
    Let base be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 0
    If base is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with base, 8, new_value_id
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: PROGRAM-LEVEL AND FUNCTION-LEVEL TRAVERSAL HELPERS
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
Whole-program optimization passes (inlining, devirtualization, tail-call,
verifier) need to iterate every function in a MIRProgram. Rather than each
pass re-implementing the offset-0 list load, this canonical accessor returns
the program's function List directly. Returning the live List (rather than a
copy) lets callers append to it cheaply when a pass needs to register new
functions, while the program retains canonical ownership of the list itself.
A null program returns 0 so the caller's standard "if functions is equal to 0"
guard handles the missing-program path uniformly with the empty-program path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRProgram offset 0, which is the canonical functions-list
slot established by create_mir_program. The MIRProgram layout (set by
create_mir_program in mir.runa) places:
  offset  0: functions List
  offset  8: function_count
  offset 16: global_values List
  offset 24: global_values_count
  offset 32: string_constants List
  offset 40: string_count
  offset 48: type_table
  offset 56: reserved
The returned List is owned by the program; callers must not destroy it.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single int64 load. Inlines to one mov on x86_64. Called once per
whole-program pass, so not on any inner loop.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read with explicit null guard. No allocation, no mutation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_program_functions" that takes program_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If program_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program_ptr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Profitability gating in optimization passes (inlining, devirtualization,
tail-call) is dramatically cheaper when the pass can skip functions that
contain no instructions of the relevant kind. Rather than each pass
re-implementing the walk-blocks-walk-instructions double loop with its own
opcode comparison, this canonical helper centralises the pattern and exposes
the single tuning knob (the opcode to match) as a parameter. The function
is read-only over its inputs, so it is safe to call from any phase including
post-pass profitability checks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walks the function's CFG and counts every instruction whose opcode equals
the requested target_opcode. The traversal pattern:
  1. From function pointer, read CFG pointer (MIRFunction offset 8).
  2. From CFG pointer, read blocks List (MIRCFG offset 16).
  3. For each block in the List, read its instructions List (MIRBasicBlock
     offset 16) and instruction_count (offset 24).
  4. For each instruction in that block, read its opcode (MIRNode offset 0)
     and increment the running tally on a match.
Returns 0 for a null function pointer or any structurally absent
sub-component (no CFG, no blocks list, no instructions list); 0 is the
correct count for "this function has no instructions of that kind",
matching what callers expect from a vacuous case.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(N) in the total instruction count of the function. Called once per
function per profitability check, not in any inner optimization loop.
The cached instruction_count at MIRBasicBlock offset 24 avoids re-walking
the per-block list to compute its length.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read with explicit null guards at every dereference level. No
allocation, no mutation, no side effects.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "count_instructions_of_type" that takes function_ptr as Integer, target_opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read CFG pointer from MIRFunction offset 8
    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function_ptr, 8
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read blocks List from MIRCFG offset 16
    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg_ptr, 16
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block_count be proc list_length from List with blocks
    Let total_count be 0
    Let block_idx be 0

    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc list_get from List with blocks, block_idx
        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Read instructions List from MIRBasicBlock offset 16
            Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 16
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Note: Read cached instruction_count from MIRBasicBlock offset 24
                Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 24
                Let inst_idx be 0
                While inst_idx is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst_ptr be proc list_get from List with instructions, inst_idx
                    If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
                        Note: Read opcode from MIRNode offset 0
                        Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 0
                        If opcode is equal to target_opcode:
                            Set total_count to total_count plus 1
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set inst_idx to inst_idx plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Return total_count
End Process
